data.text:
Douglas Gorman and Tom McGouran have kindly produced the following list of players who won Junior International caps. Their book, “Junior Scotland 1889 to 2019: The Players and Matches”, gives details of 421 international and friendly matches played by Junior Scotland over 130 years. It also includes 11 matches that were postponed or abandoned to complete the listing. The details of each match also includes, when it could be found, the attendance and gate receipts.

Douglas and Tom have been able to identify 2,426 players from those matches and their Junior Scotland record, together with goals scored and if they captained the team, is all included in the individual listing of each player.

Their book is available from the Lulu self-publishing website using the following link:

Junior Scotland 1889 to 2019: The Players and Matches (lulu.com)

The book retails at £9.50 plus postage & packaging. When ordering you should go to the dark blue banner at the bottom of the screen and change “USD” to “GBP”.

Since the book was published Douglas and Tom have continued their research finding a few more previously unknown friendly matches and, in some cases, adding missing forenames or correcting the spelling of the names of players. At the time of writing their records include 448 matches and 2,530 players including travelling reserves. They are trying particularly hard to find a forename(s) or even a first initial(s) for these international players or travelling reserves:

Current clubs - Blantyre Victoria - Robertson (1915), Cambuslang Rangers [2] - McIntosh (1921), Darvel - Findlay (1927), Dunipace Juniors - Taylor (1927), Cairns (1928), Glasgow Perthshire - Bennie (1927), Renfrew - Brown (1916 & 1920).

Defunct clubs - Airdrieonians 'A' - McKinlay (1896), Benburb [1] - Leslie (1890), Burnbank Athletic [2] - Hunter (1927), Thomson (1920), Corporation Cleansing Department (Govan) - Wilson (1928), Dalziel Rovers - Irvine (1907), Douglas Water Thistle - Henderson (1913), Drongan - Morrison (1920), Dumbarton Juniors [2] - Hislop (1923), Dunaskin Lads - Logan (1921), Dundee Arnot - Graham (1908), Duntocher Hibernian [1] - Grieve (1904), Hamilton West End Rangers - Sneddon (1890), Moore Park - Hosie (1897), Muirkirk Athletic - Grant (1915), Renfrew Victoria - Leitch (1910), Shawbank - Wilson (1894).

There are a few important points to note about the list of players:

Where a player was capped at more than one club then there is a separate line for each club.

Some of these players were also capped for Scotland at full or amateur levels and you will find details of these players using the following link:

Scotland - Double Internationals (rsssf.com)

The number after the players’ name and club is the number of international matches played. There have been 264 international matches. It does not include players who:

Played in matches that might be considered at first sight to be internationals but do not meet the authors’ definition. These include tours to Norway (1921) and the then West Germany (1975) together with a single Under-23 international (including two over-age players) in 1994.

Were awarded with caps as travelling reserves. Before the days of substitutes one player accompanied the team as a travelling reserve. However, they are only included in the list if they took part in the match either as a last-minute replacement or, very occasionally, coming on during the game for an injured player.

If a number in brackets is added after:

the player’s name it differentiates him from a player(s) with the same first initial(s) and surname.

the club’s name it differentiates it from earlier/later clubs that shared the same name.

If you cannot find a player you may be looking for remember:

A few matches were postponed. Players selected for these matches are not included in the list but are included in the details in the book.

there are nearly 700 other players included in the book who played for Junior Scotland in a wide range of matches that are not classified as international matches.

the term “Junior Internationalist” was a term used by the newspapers to also describe players who played for their League select team against the Irish Intermediate League and would have been presented with a cap.
